{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> εὔχομαι</b>, <br /> <i>imperfect</i> εὐχόμην (<i>Attic dialect</i> ηὐ-) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 3.275, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: <i>future</i> εὔξομαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Aves” 622 (_anapaest meter_), etc.: \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<i>aorist 1</i> εὐξάμην (<i>Attic dialect</i> ηὐ-) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 8.254, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: <i>2nd pers.</i> <i>singular</i> <i>subjunctive</i> εὔξεαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 3.45: (augment ηὐ\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]- only <i>Attic dialect</i><i>accusative</i> to Hdn.[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"Gr. 2.789, 2nd c.AD: Moeris Grammaticus 175)\">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]: —<b>pray</b>, θεοῖς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 3.296, 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 8.64, 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 3.58, etc.; ἀγάλμασι 1st c.AD(?): Heraclitus 5; ἀνέμοισι 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 7.178; Ἀργείοισι 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Supplices” 980: c._accusative_ _cognate_, εὐχὰς εὔ. τοῖς θεοῖς 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 19.130 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; εὐχὰς ὑπέρ τινος πρὸς τοὺς θεοὺς εὔ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aeschines Orator 3.18 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; εὔ. ἔπος <b>to utter</b> it <b>in prayer</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Simonides Lyricus 37.19, 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 3.2, 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Supplices” 1059 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; μεγάλα, μέγα εὔ., <b>pray</b> aloud, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 3.275, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 17.239; πολλὰ Ποσειδάωνι 3.54: later, c._accusative_, Ἄρτεμιν εὔ. “Anthologia Graeca” 9.268 (Antip. Thess.): _absolutely_, 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 7.298, 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Choephori” 465 (Lyric poetry), 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Fragmenta” 39 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator (Lyric poetry), etc. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> with <i>accusative</i> et <i>infinitive</i>, <b>pray that</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 15.353, 21.211, 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.31 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; of an unrealizable wish [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"compare (εὐχή 2), 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Ethica Nicomachea” 1118a32, compare 3rd c.BC: Macho Comicus cited in 2nd c.AD: Athenaeus Epigrammaticus 8.341d \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]: with <i>infinitive</i> alone, εὔ. θάνατον φυγεῖν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 2.401 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; τί δοκέεις εὔχεσθαι ἄλλο ἢ.. λαβεῖ; [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.27; οἶκον ἰδεῖν 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 4.293, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τοῖς θεοῖς with <i>accusative</i> et <i>infinitive</i>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedo” 117c \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; also εὔ. τοὺς θεοὺς δοῦναί μοι <b>pray</b> that the gods may give, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Thesmophoriazusae” 351, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 6.1.26; πρὸς τοὺς θεοὺς διδόναι [prev. author] “Mem.” 1.3.2; ταῖς Μούσαις εἰπεῖν 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 545d, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; later εὔ. ἵνα[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" Aristeas 45, 1st c.BC: Dionysius Halicarnassensis 9.53, 2nd c.AD: Arrianus Historicus “Epicteti Dissertationes” 2.6.12; ὅπως “Wien.Stud.” 44.159. \">Refs 1st c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__3</b></Level3> with <i>accusative</i> <i>object</i>, <b>pray for, long</b> or <b>wish for</b>, χρυσόν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “N.” 8.37, etc.; εὐχόμενος ἄν τις ταῦτα εὔξαιτο 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 6.1 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; εὔ. τινί τι <b>pray for</b> something <b>for</b> a person, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 1019; κακόν τινι 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator 21.21 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; also, <b>pray for</b> a thing <b>from</b>.., τοῖς θεοῖς πολλὰ ἀγαθὰ ὑπέρ τινος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Memorabilia” 2.2.10 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τοῖς θεοῖς πολυκαρπίαν[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 3.14.3; δεινὸν κατά τινος 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Abd.” 32. \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <b>vow</b> or <b>promise to</b> do.., with <i>future</i> <i>infinitive</i>, εὔχομαι ἐξελάαν κύνας [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 8.526; θεοῖσι.. ἑκατόμβας ῥέξειν 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 17.50, compare 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 4.101, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedo” 58b, “IG” 12.108.55, 22.112.6 (4th c.BC): with \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<i>aorist</i> <i>infinitive</i>, εὔχετο πάντ᾽ ἀποδοῦναι <b>claimed</b> (the right) to pay in full, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 18.499 (unless in signification 111.3): with \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<i>present</i> <i>infinitive</i>, ηὔξω θεοῖς.. ἂν ὧδ᾽ ἔρδειν τάδ; [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 933, compare 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 1032 codices \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> with <i>accusative</i> <i>of things</i>, <b>vow</b> a thing, πολλῶν πατησμὸν εἱμάτων [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 963; ἱερεῖον 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Aves” 1619; [λύχνον] περὶ παιδός 3rd c.BC: Callimachus Epicus “Epigrammata” 56.3. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.3</b></Level3> εὔ. κατά τινος of the thing vowed (as though on the altar), εὔ. τοῖς θεοῖς κατὰ ἑκατόμβης [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Marius” 26, compare 2.294b; κατὰ νικητηρίων 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator “Epistulae” 1.16. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> <b>profess loudly, boast, vaunt</b>, οὕτω φησὶ καὶ εὔχεται, οὕνεκ᾽ Ἀχιλλεὺς νηυσὶν ἔπι γλαφυρῇσι μένει [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 14.366; εὑρεῖν 5th c.BC: Empedocles Poeta Philosophus 2.6 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: mostly, not of empty boasting, but of something of which one has a right to be proud, ταύτης τοι γενεῆς τε καὶ αἵματος εὔχομαι εἶναι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 6.211, compare 8.190; πατρὸς δ᾽ ἐξ ἀγαθοῦ καὶ ἐγὼ γένος εὔχομαι εἶναι 14.113, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Gorgias” 449a: rarely without \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<i>infinitive</i>, ἐκ Κρητάων γένος εὔχομαι (i.e. εἶναι) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 14.199; τὸ πατρόθεν ἐκ Διὸς εὔχονται 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 7.23, compare “P.” 4.97 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; πόρτις εὔχεται βοός (i.e. εἶναι) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Supplices” 314; ἔνθεν εὔχομαι γένος 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Fragmenta” 696 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; but also, <br /><Level3><b>__III.2</b></Level3> <b>boast vainlv, brag</b>, εὔχεαι αὔτως [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 11.388 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: with <i>infinitive</i>, εὔ. δῃώσειν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 1318. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__III.3</b></Level3> simply, <b>profess</b> or <b>declare</b>, ἱκέτης δέ τοι εὔ. εἶναι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 5.450; οὔτ᾽ ὦν ἀκοῦσαι οὔτ᾽ ἰδεῖν εὔχοντο 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 6.53 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; τίς χθὼν εὔχεται ἥδε [εἶναι]; [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.BC: Apollonius Rhodius Epicus 4.1251; compare above 11.1. \">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__IV</b></Level2> <i>passive</i>, ἐμοὶ μετρίως ηὖκται I <b>have prayed</b> sufficiently, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedrus” 279c \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>perfect</i> <i>infinitive</i>, ταῦτα μὲν ηὖχθαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “IG” 22.112.12 (4th c.BC)\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; ἡ πανήγυρις ἡ.. εὐχθεῖσα <b>vowed</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd-3rd c.AD: Dio Cassius Historicus 48.32: but \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]<i>pluperfect</i> (or non-thematic preterite) ηὔγμην in <i>active</i> sense, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 610; so εὖκτο Thebaïs “fragment” 3 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]. (Cf. Sanskrit <i>óhate</i> 'to (be able to) boast that one is', 'to brag', Avest. <b>aog</b>- 'declare solemnly'.)","strongNumber":"G2172","accentedUnicode":"εὔχομαι","relatedNos":[{"strongNumber":"G2171","matchingForm":"εὐχή","stepTransliteration":"euchē","gloss":"a vow/prayer","_zh_tw_Gloss":"願, 禱告","_es_Gloss":"un juramiento/oración","_zh_Gloss":"愿, 祷告"},{"strongNumber":"G4335","matchingForm":"προσευχή","stepTransliteration":"proseuchē","gloss":"prayer","_zh_tw_Gloss":"禱告","_es_Gloss":"oración","_zh_Gloss":"祷告"},{"strongNumber":"G4336","matchingForm":"προσεύχομαι","stepTransliteration":"proseuchomai","gloss":"to pray","_zh_tw_Gloss":"禱告","_es_Gloss":"orar","_zh_Gloss":"祷告"}],"shortDef":"to pray for; wish for","mediumDef":"to pray for; wish for <br /><b>to pray, offer prayer,</b> <ref='Act.26.29'>Acts 26:29;</ref> <ref='2Co.13.7'>2Cor. 13:7</ref>, 9; <ref='Jas.5.16'>Jas. 5:16;</ref> <b>to wish, desire,</b> <ref='Act.27.29'>Act